WEBVTT

00:14.416 --> 00:18.083
<i>First of all, there are some things</i>
<i>you should know before we begin.</i>

00:18.166 --> 00:22.458
<i>For instance, we are real people,</i>
<i>just like you.</i>

00:22.708 --> 00:25.208
<i>Secondly,</i>
<i>we did not write a word of this.</i>

00:25.375 --> 00:26.625
<i>To be perfectly frank, </i>

00:26.708 --> 00:29.500
<i>we would have preferred</i>
<i>all of this remain a secret.</i>

00:29.625 --> 00:31.791
<i>But we had no choice</i>
<i>in the matter.</i>

00:31.875 --> 00:35.333
<i>We just woke up one day</i>
<i>and everything changed.</i>

00:35.500 --> 00:37.875
<i>There were stories about us</i>
<i>everywhere:</i>

00:38.125 --> 00:40.666
<i>TV, newspapers, and the internet.</i>

00:40.916 --> 00:44.166
<i>And now it is our turn</i>
<i>to tell a few stories.</i>

00:44.458 --> 00:47.916
<i>Think of them as fairy tales</i>
<i>that actually happened.</i>

00:48.375 --> 00:51.750
<i>Don't worry,</i>
<i>these stories are not just about us.</i>

00:52.250 --> 00:53.791
<i>They're also about you.</i>

00:54.041 --> 00:55.833
<i>And how is that possible?</i>

00:56.166 --> 01:00.166
<i>Because all these stories</i>
<i>are about money.</i>

01:00.500 --> 01:04.041
<i>The idea of money.</i>
<i>The necessity of money.</i>

01:04.583 --> 01:07.125
<i>The secret life of money.</i>

01:07.333 --> 01:10.375
Before money,
there was only the barter system.

01:10.458 --> 01:14.500
You tried to trade what you had
or you could do for what you needed.

01:14.708 --> 01:17.166
You have bananas, but you need a cow.

01:17.541 --> 01:19.833
I have a cow, but I hate bananas.

01:19.916 --> 01:23.416
So, as you can imagine,
there was a limit to this system.

01:23.625 --> 01:27.708
Bananas turn brown over time
and cows can, you know, wander away.

01:27.791 --> 01:31.458
So an agreed-upon
medium of exchange was needed.

01:31.833 --> 01:33.916
What is a medium of exchange?

01:34.791 --> 01:38.000
-Well, it could be a... a nugget of gold.

01:38.083 --> 01:41.833
Or some other shiny rocks
that are generally found to be scarce.

01:42.333 --> 01:45.583
It could be a... a slip of paper

01:46.458 --> 01:47.708
-with words on it...
-Aah!

01:47.791 --> 01:49.875
...or pictures of powerful people.

01:50.250 --> 01:51.666
And if you read those words,

01:51.750 --> 01:55.958
you will see that they are arranged
into a promise of value.

02:00.833 --> 02:02.458
-Slips of paper...

02:02.541 --> 02:06.708
...which you cannot peel and eat,
and do not give milk

02:06.791 --> 02:09.125
are what we all agreed
to call "money."

02:09.416 --> 02:14.083
And these slips gave birth
to many other pieces of paper

02:14.166 --> 02:17.166
-with more writing on them.

02:17.250 --> 02:23.083
And some of those words,
they told the story of credit.

02:24.291 --> 02:26.666
Oh, stay with us now,
this is important.

02:27.625 --> 02:33.375
Credit is an invention that meant
you no longer needed to carry around, uh,

02:33.583 --> 02:36.375
millions of bananas on slips of paper.

02:36.458 --> 02:39.250
So, you now have something invisible,
credit,

02:39.333 --> 02:42.291
standing in for something tangible,
a cow.

02:42.375 --> 02:44.458
Credit said that even if you didn't have

02:44.625 --> 02:47.583
all the bananas you need
for what you want,

02:48.208 --> 02:50.416
you could borrow bananas

02:50.958 --> 02:52.666
from the future.

02:52.750 --> 02:57.250
So, credit is just the future tense
of the language of money.

02:59.250 --> 03:01.125
Speaking of the future...

03:01.500 --> 03:04.958
Uh, things have gotten
a little more complicated.

03:05.041 --> 03:07.500
Actually, a lot more complicated.

03:07.583 --> 03:10.833
There is more money than ever before.

03:10.916 --> 03:13.666
Our money has more names
than ever before.

03:13.750 --> 03:18.166
Commodities, loans, stocks, and bonds.

03:18.250 --> 03:21.000
Funds and funds of funds.

03:21.083 --> 03:24.666
Futures, equity,
derivatives, securitized debt,

03:24.750 --> 03:26.208
shorts and margin calls.

03:26.291 --> 03:28.000
Financial instruments.

03:28.166 --> 03:29.208
Words.

03:29.583 --> 03:31.333
-Invisible.

03:31.416 --> 03:32.583
Abstract.

03:33.708 --> 03:35.583
Very different from cows.

04:02.625 --> 04:04.416
Morning has broken.

04:04.500 --> 04:06.291
- Morning.
-Mwah!

04:06.458 --> 04:08.416
-Come on, buddy.
-What time is it?

04:08.500 --> 04:09.916
It's time.

04:10.500 --> 04:12.583
Did you remember to take all your--

04:12.666 --> 04:13.500
Yes!

04:14.041 --> 04:17.208
-You didn't even let me finish.
-I took them, I took everything.

04:18.083 --> 04:19.541
-Big fat liar.
-I'm not.

04:19.625 --> 04:21.583
You know,
they're not gonna wait for us, Joe.

04:21.666 --> 04:22.625
Okay, yeah.

04:22.708 --> 04:24.458
-So....
-I can't do the laces.

04:24.541 --> 04:27.041
-You can have this. I'll take this off.
-No, I'm all right.

04:27.125 --> 04:29.791
-I think it's gonna warm up.
-Oh, look. They haven't left yet.

04:29.875 --> 04:31.958
-No, no, we're all right.
- Oh, gosh.

04:32.041 --> 04:33.041
We're all right.

04:33.958 --> 04:35.416
If they ask about it.

04:35.500 --> 04:37.000
-They'll save a place for us.
-Yeah.

04:37.083 --> 04:38.583
-You think?
-Yeah.

04:38.750 --> 04:40.625
-There they are.
-Drop a line in.

04:40.708 --> 04:41.958
What would you catch?

04:42.333 --> 04:44.125
-Oh, here's Barb. Hi.
-Probably an old boot.

04:44.208 --> 04:47.333
-Hey. Sorry.
-The line's movin', it's okay.

04:47.416 --> 04:49.291
Tryin' to move him out is like,
you know...

04:49.375 --> 04:50.333
Yep.

04:50.791 --> 04:53.750
All right. Yeah, that's great.
I'm glad. I didn't remember.

04:55.166 --> 04:57.166
-Shall we let them go, or...
-Uh...

04:58.791 --> 04:59.791
That's it.

04:59.875 --> 05:02.958
-Careful on this thing, it gets tricky.
-Yeah, it gets a little slippery.

05:04.125 --> 05:05.583
-Okay.
-Thank you.

05:08.250 --> 05:09.208
Honey?

05:09.583 --> 05:11.291
Yeah? Oh, look, a place. Oh.

05:12.041 --> 05:13.541
-Oh, and leg room..
-Yeah.

05:13.625 --> 05:14.458
...to boot.

05:15.791 --> 05:16.625
Sweet.

05:30.000 --> 05:31.708
Good afternoon, Trenton travelers.

05:32.125 --> 05:33.250
This is Richard Paris.

05:33.333 --> 05:36.500
I'll be your captain here
on historic Lake George.

05:36.583 --> 05:42.208
We got a magnificent fall day,
so sit back and relax and enjoy the view.

05:44.166 --> 05:45.708
Posh seats, huh?

05:45.791 --> 05:46.833
-No.

05:46.916 --> 05:49.625
Hey, you know where
the word "posh" comes from?

05:49.708 --> 05:51.875
-Do you know, Barb?
-No idea, El.

05:52.166 --> 05:54.500
Oh, is this one
of your crossword puzzle things

05:54.583 --> 05:57.625
-or a fun fact off a calendar?
- Go on, tell her.

05:57.833 --> 06:00.375
The posh seats on a boat, the good seats,

06:00.583 --> 06:04.291
were called that because when cruises went
from England to Africa,

06:04.375 --> 06:07.833
if you were sitting on the port side
on the way there, you saw land.

06:07.916 --> 06:11.625
Yeah, and when you would go back,
you'd want to sit on the starboard side,

06:11.708 --> 06:14.291
so that you're not
lookin' out at nothing all day.

06:14.666 --> 06:16.958
Port Out, Starboard Home.

06:17.333 --> 06:20.541
P-O-S-H. It's... It's a... an acronym.

06:20.625 --> 06:21.458
Yeah.

06:21.958 --> 06:24.166
Boy, you guys sure know a lot of trivia.

06:24.625 --> 06:28.041
Well, you weren't just staring at nothing.

06:28.125 --> 06:32.833
I-- I mean, if you had eyes at all,
you'd be looking at something.

06:32.916 --> 06:36.458
Maybe clouds or whales, but something.

06:38.666 --> 06:39.666
Maybe.

06:39.833 --> 06:41.791
All right, comin' up
on your right-hand side

06:41.875 --> 06:43.958
just a couple meters beneath the surface

06:45.041 --> 06:47.583
is the Sunken Fleet of 1758.

06:48.500 --> 06:51.500
- Oh, that's what that is.
-British soldiers stationed on the lake

06:51.583 --> 06:54.291
sank over 260 vessels to keep them

06:54.375 --> 06:56.916
-from being captured by the French.
- Amazing it's lasted.

06:58.000 --> 06:58.958
Captain?

07:01.916 --> 07:03.833
Ah, shit, where did that come from?

07:10.416 --> 07:11.625
Whoa!

07:41.333 --> 07:44.541
Ellen and Joe went on their honeymoon
in Niagara Falls

07:44.625 --> 07:47.833
and they were on their way back there
the day we lost Joe.

07:49.000 --> 07:54.000
His dear friend Norm Sidley told me that
Joe had a ruby pendant in his pocket

07:54.083 --> 07:56.375
that he planned to give to Ellen
at the Falls,

07:56.458 --> 07:58.208
because a 40th anniversary...

07:59.875 --> 08:00.875
is ruby,

08:02.166 --> 08:03.750
a stone of uncommon beauty.

08:05.541 --> 08:07.416
And Joe Martin was just as rare.

08:09.500 --> 08:12.875
The common man has become
anything but that.

08:14.500 --> 08:17.041
Men who love their wives without stopping.

08:17.125 --> 08:19.833
Men who are there for their children
without fail.

08:20.333 --> 08:23.791
Men who pay their taxes
and shovel their neighbor's walk.

08:25.125 --> 08:28.500
Men who drive the speed limit, even
when there's nobody there to watch them.

08:28.708 --> 08:32.166
This is the 14th of 21 funerals

08:32.500 --> 08:35.166
that this tragedy has visited
upon our community.

08:37.125 --> 08:40.582
Each one sharpening the pain
of our shared loss.

08:44.250 --> 08:48.375
So... So, what happens next?
What do we do next?

08:49.250 --> 08:53.583
Well, uh, Shoreline Cruises,
like most of these outfits,

08:53.666 --> 08:56.125
they have insurance
for accidents and such.

08:56.958 --> 09:00.791
And that involves filing a claim,
which they have done with the carrier.

09:00.875 --> 09:05.250
So basically, they drowned Joe
and 20 other innocent people,

09:05.333 --> 09:07.333
and you can get insurance for that?

09:08.500 --> 09:14.250
You know, Gwen Musgrave says that she can
still feel Bucky Mecklenberg's actual hand

09:14.625 --> 09:19.125
on her leg, pullin' it, tryin' to get up
to the surface to get the air.

09:19.458 --> 09:22.875
You know, she feels it in the middle
of the night, just layin' there.

09:24.666 --> 09:27.000
Drowning man's hand on her leg. Whew.

09:27.458 --> 09:29.666
What kind of compensation is there
for that?

09:30.125 --> 09:33.916
Well, Shoreline is tellin' me that they
bought a policy from one company

09:34.000 --> 09:36.791
and then they were reinsured
through another company.

09:37.541 --> 09:42.416
But I'm expecting a settlement offer
in the mid-seven figures as a start.

09:42.666 --> 09:44.041
Here's what they're saying.

09:44.125 --> 09:45.416
-Who?
-United.

09:46.416 --> 09:49.083
I thought our insurance was
through that firm Monarch.

09:49.166 --> 09:50.208
It was. Uh--

09:50.291 --> 09:52.625
We did. Well, actually, GPOA.

09:52.958 --> 09:54.000
And what's that?

09:54.083 --> 09:57.666
Global Property Owners Association.
That's who insured this place.

09:57.750 --> 09:59.791
And they insured the boat as well.

10:00.291 --> 10:01.875
-So what's Monarch?

10:01.958 --> 10:04.083
GPOA became Monarch.

10:04.458 --> 10:07.000
But now this guy, Mr. Purser,

10:07.083 --> 10:12.250
is saying that Monarch itself is insured
by-- by a firm called, uh, United.

10:13.333 --> 10:16.583
So United takes over the policy
from Monarch.

10:18.083 --> 10:19.666
So United is gonna pay.

10:20.375 --> 10:23.291
That's the thing. We got this note saying,

10:24.333 --> 10:26.833
"The money you have already saved
on your insurance

10:26.916 --> 10:30.333
is nothing in comparison to having
an accident with one of your boats

10:30.416 --> 10:32.958
while operating them on the lake,
where they have no coverage.

10:33.750 --> 10:36.541
I strongly urge you
to reconsider the quote

10:36.625 --> 10:39.833
for marine liability and hull coverage
on your entire fleet.

10:40.041 --> 10:42.583
I realize that you know the lake
much better than we do

10:42.666 --> 10:46.666
and you have never had an accident before,
but this is our recommendation to you."

10:47.625 --> 10:50.250
No coverage? Who said that?

10:50.333 --> 10:51.666
Purser at Monarch.

10:52.041 --> 10:54.083
But I thought you said Monarch is United.

10:54.166 --> 10:55.208
Right, it is.

10:55.291 --> 10:57.916
And Monarch is saying
that our policy expired be--

10:58.791 --> 11:00.041
before the accident,

11:00.375 --> 11:02.541
so United is off the hook.

11:04.916 --> 11:06.041
Jesus.

11:07.208 --> 11:08.291
You let it lapse?

11:08.375 --> 11:11.541
-No. No, I--
-And we're gonna be exposed here?

11:11.625 --> 11:13.750
-Us personally?
-No. It's not true...

11:14.083 --> 11:14.916
Rich.

11:19.375 --> 11:20.708
You gonna answer?

11:22.916 --> 11:25.041
What area code is 518? You know?

11:25.666 --> 11:27.916
- Europe?

11:28.083 --> 11:30.708
It's not Europe.
Europe have different numbers.

11:30.791 --> 11:32.750
If you answered, you could ask.

11:34.791 --> 11:37.625
You didn't sign these, Irvin.

11:37.708 --> 11:41.083
These were supposed to be sent back
to Mossack Fonseca days ago.

11:44.625 --> 11:48.916
RDPS Trading, TEP Consulting,
Wilkinson Systems Limited.

11:49.000 --> 11:52.166
You need to be signing where it says
"Director" on all of these.

11:52.625 --> 11:55.625
I need to fax these back to Panama
by the end of the day.

11:57.041 --> 11:57.875
Irvin!

12:02.875 --> 12:05.500
That's $15 a signature, sweetie.

12:08.750 --> 12:11.708
Also, Christopher Purser
called from Houston,

12:11.791 --> 12:15.000
said there's a problem
with the Monarch-United arrangement.

12:15.083 --> 12:16.416
What kinda problem?

12:17.041 --> 12:18.500
Boat sank in New York.

12:20.000 --> 12:22.708
Twenty-one people died.
He wants to know what to do.

12:22.791 --> 12:24.625
You want me to get him on the phone?

12:33.708 --> 12:37.166
<i>Hey, this is Matthew Quirk</i>
<i>calling for Mr. Boncamper.</i>

12:37.250 --> 12:41.250
<i>Uh, my lawyer says you're the nominee</i>
<i>director for United Reinsurance.</i>

12:41.333 --> 12:44.375
<i>I filed an accident claim</i>
<i>for Shoreline Cruises</i>

12:44.458 --> 12:46.875
<i>and I need to speak with you</i>
<i>as soon as possible.</i>

12:46.958 --> 12:48.958
<i>My number is area code 518--</i>

12:49.375 --> 12:50.333
Shit.

12:50.791 --> 12:52.291
I got some bad news.

12:54.000 --> 12:56.875
A very unfortunate turn of events.

12:57.791 --> 13:01.333
Mr. Purser, who sold us the policy
down in Houston

13:01.416 --> 13:03.458
is, um... under investigation

13:03.541 --> 13:07.666
by some sort of professional
oversight organization there in Texas.

13:07.750 --> 13:09.916
He's not allowed
to sell insurance anymore.

13:10.375 --> 13:12.875
Ever. The IRS is involved.

13:12.958 --> 13:18.208
There were gyms with claims
and, uh, nursing homes with claims.

13:19.708 --> 13:21.041
We're not the only ones.

13:21.833 --> 13:24.000
Uh, they said, "Get in line."

13:28.208 --> 13:30.125
I was tryin' to save some money, Rich.

13:32.833 --> 13:36.375
And they were cheaper.
Monarch was... they were much cheaper.

13:37.166 --> 13:40.708
We were expanding the restaurant
and buying a second boat.

13:42.000 --> 13:44.583
Matty, they're gonna come
after us, aren't they?

13:46.625 --> 13:49.125
I can't sleep at night. Um...

13:50.166 --> 13:52.208
I have dreams about those people.

13:54.166 --> 13:58.083
Faces floating up in the waves,
bodies washin' up on the beach.

13:58.166 --> 13:59.166
Beach by my house.

14:03.541 --> 14:05.500
Maybe we could try to settle with 'em.

14:05.750 --> 14:08.833
Of course, we--
Of course, we want to settle.

14:10.750 --> 14:12.958
We are hat in hand here, Rich.

14:14.416 --> 14:17.958
Hat in hand, wanting to settle
with the best of intentions.

14:29.583 --> 14:31.583
-What do you think?
-Let's go!

14:31.666 --> 14:32.833
-Whoo!
-Whoa!

14:32.916 --> 14:34.625
I know! Automatic!

14:37.708 --> 14:40.291
-Sometimes I get lost. Okay...
-This way?

14:40.375 --> 14:41.875
-All the way down there.
- Whoo!

14:41.958 --> 14:43.458
There, right to the elevator.

14:43.916 --> 14:45.541
-Good boy.
-Oh, wow.

14:45.625 --> 14:47.041
-Whoa!

14:47.125 --> 14:49.875
-Waah-oooh!
-Whoo!

14:49.958 --> 14:51.833
-I'm gonna catch you!
-No, you're not!

14:51.916 --> 14:54.375
-Oh, Mom, this is so great.
-I know.

14:55.875 --> 14:57.333
Think your dad would approve?

14:58.458 --> 15:00.166
-He'd love it, Mom.
- Come on!

15:00.416 --> 15:02.000
- Oh, no!
-I think so too.

15:02.083 --> 15:04.625
Hey, kids, come here, come here. Look.

15:05.166 --> 15:07.000
-Can you see the Eiffel Tower?
-What?

15:07.083 --> 15:08.583
-Can you see it?
-Yeah.

15:08.666 --> 15:10.208
It looks like Paris, France.

15:11.083 --> 15:12.916
-Wait.
-Can you see? Kaylen, look.

15:13.500 --> 15:15.916
They light it up all night long.
It's so pretty.

15:16.000 --> 15:18.083
But here's the best, best, best part.

15:18.500 --> 15:19.958
Can you see by the palm tree?

15:20.166 --> 15:21.833
-Oh, yes, I can.
-Yeah.

15:23.458 --> 15:27.708
Years ago, there was a guy there who
could write your name on a grain of rice.

15:27.791 --> 15:30.125
-What?
-For 25 cents.

15:30.208 --> 15:31.708
-That's a bargain.
-I know.

15:31.791 --> 15:33.416
-Whoa.
-And...

15:33.791 --> 15:38.458
that corner is the corner
where I met your grandfather.

15:40.125 --> 15:41.708
-Oh.

15:42.333 --> 15:44.083
He was here for a tire convention,

15:44.166 --> 15:48.375
and I was here
'cause my girlfriend's bachelorette party.

15:49.000 --> 15:52.666
And he took me to see Diana Ross
at Caesars.

15:53.291 --> 15:55.250
How he got those tickets...

15:55.375 --> 15:58.208
Although he did tell me later
that he stole 'em

15:58.291 --> 16:00.458
-out of his boss's briefcase.

16:00.541 --> 16:02.750
-Which is bad.

16:03.291 --> 16:06.875
But he said that he knew her from Detroit.

16:07.250 --> 16:08.708
He sold her tires.

16:09.208 --> 16:12.541
This is one of the Supremes.
I don't think so.

16:13.875 --> 16:16.416
Anyway, she came out onstage and he said,

16:17.708 --> 16:22.375
"The most beautiful woman
I have ever seen in my whole life."

16:25.000 --> 16:28.000
But then he leaned over to me
and he said, "Except for you."

16:29.041 --> 16:30.250
-Aw.
-Was he kidding?

16:30.500 --> 16:32.916
Oh! "Was he kidding?"

16:35.875 --> 16:40.458
So, I was supposed to drive back
to Sacramento with Connie, but I didn't.

16:40.791 --> 16:44.083
I stayed the whole weekend,
'cause it was Labor Day weekend.

16:44.208 --> 16:48.208
And we, uh... we went to the Jerry Lewis
muscular dystrophy telethon,

16:48.291 --> 16:49.583
saw that live.

16:50.333 --> 16:53.916
We went and got mai tai
after mai tai after mai tai.

16:54.000 --> 16:55.458
What's a mai tai?

16:55.833 --> 16:58.625
Oh, that's a Hawaiian
fertility drug, honey.

16:59.000 --> 17:00.625
-Mom.

17:01.041 --> 17:04.000
Your mom was conceived
under a paper umbrella

17:04.083 --> 17:06.583
when we were $68 up at slots.

17:06.708 --> 17:09.290
Yeah!

17:09.415 --> 17:11.790
Okay, listen, kids,
why don't you put your swimsuits on?

17:11.875 --> 17:13.458
-There is a pool on the roof.
-Really?

17:13.540 --> 17:15.290
-Yeah.
-Oh, my goodness.

17:16.165 --> 17:18.500
-Pool, here I come.
-Pool, here I come.

17:19.375 --> 17:20.208
Whoo!

17:20.290 --> 17:21.833
-Mrs. Martin?
- Yeah?

17:22.333 --> 17:23.500
-Hi, Hannah!
-Hi--

17:23.583 --> 17:25.290
-This is my daughter, Melanie.
-Hi.

17:25.375 --> 17:27.000
-Did you get my message?
-And my grandkid--

17:27.083 --> 17:28.875
-What? No, what me--
-I left you a message.

17:28.958 --> 17:32.833
Oh. Well, I've been so busy with
the yard sale and the packing and the--

17:32.916 --> 17:35.125
I'm not sure my mom knows how
to check her messages.

17:35.208 --> 17:37.166
I've been stayin' with her
out in Denver, so--

17:37.250 --> 17:40.166
Hey, let me-- Kids, come here.
I want you to meet somebody.

17:40.666 --> 17:41.916
-This is...
-Hello!

17:42.000 --> 17:43.958
...Kaylen! And this is Thalia.

17:44.041 --> 17:45.291
-Hello!
-Ah.

17:45.375 --> 17:48.083
She is a great butterfly swimmer.

17:48.166 --> 17:49.125
Mwah!

17:49.208 --> 17:50.541
Olympic hopeful.

17:50.625 --> 17:51.833
Bet you got your swimsuit on

17:51.916 --> 17:53.666
-underneath that shirt, don't you?
-Yeah!

17:53.750 --> 17:55.125
Pick me up!

17:55.208 --> 17:58.208
Do you-- Do you just--
I'd like to speak to you for a minute.

17:58.291 --> 18:00.291
-If we could just....
-Oh, sure, sure.

18:00.375 --> 18:02.041
Okay, we're gonna go swimming soon.

18:02.125 --> 18:04.000
-Here, wait here.
-Mom, I wanna go swimming.

18:04.083 --> 18:06.083
-Let's play I Spy. What do you see?
- Me too.

18:06.166 --> 18:08.208
-What do you see?
- I spy something blue.

18:10.041 --> 18:11.541
This unit's been sold.

18:12.291 --> 18:13.916
-What?
-Not to you.

18:16.041 --> 18:17.708
Well, where-- Can't I-- Wh--

18:18.750 --> 18:22.208
What's the word? Counter? Counter.
Can't I even counter?

18:22.708 --> 18:25.333
They paid double the asking price.
In cash.

18:26.041 --> 18:28.708
And they bought three units
that they want to combine.

18:29.833 --> 18:31.541
So what do I-- What happens to me?

18:32.291 --> 18:35.625
Well, I have a wonderful
one-bedroom Bristol.

18:36.000 --> 18:37.958
It has Italian marble everywhere.

18:38.041 --> 18:40.625
-I don't care about marble.
-I could show you. It'd be great.

18:40.708 --> 18:43.125
No, I don't care.
I just want to look out and see Joe.

18:44.291 --> 18:46.750
-Joe?
-I want to look out and see my corner.

18:48.625 --> 18:51.583
Well, okay. I don't have anything
facing that direction,

18:51.666 --> 18:58.166
but I do have a three-bedroom Hennessey
facing north.

18:58.250 --> 18:59.416
-It's gorgeous.
-No.

18:59.500 --> 19:00.750
-I could show you that?
-No.

19:00.833 --> 19:02.541
-No, not north.
-It's really wonderful.

19:02.625 --> 19:04.375
-I could--
-Fuck north. No.

19:04.791 --> 19:07.875
I am puttin' down the settlement money
from the accident.

19:09.333 --> 19:12.041
I look out there
and I see him smilin' at me,

19:12.125 --> 19:13.500
holdin' two tickets.

19:13.583 --> 19:14.583
You see who?

19:14.666 --> 19:17.166
Two tickets to the rest of my life.

19:18.416 --> 19:23.625
I walk around Detroit, I see him reachin'
up for dead leaves in a lake.

19:26.166 --> 19:29.000
If these people,
whoever they are, if they knew...

19:29.291 --> 19:30.708
I could explain it to 'em.

19:31.041 --> 19:34.958
-There are so many places they could live.
-I can't give you their name, by law.

19:35.041 --> 19:37.375
-Maybe you could talk to their lawyer.

19:37.458 --> 19:39.500
That's right.
I could write 'em a letter.

19:39.583 --> 19:42.083
That wouldn't be
an invasion of anybody's privacy.

19:42.166 --> 19:44.958
-I can't give you their name.
-Or if I could just talk to 'em.

19:45.041 --> 19:46.541
-Why?
-Privacy.

19:47.041 --> 19:50.583
Cash. Who pays cash?

19:51.458 --> 19:52.583
Russians.

19:55.083 --> 19:57.250
Aren't we going swimming?

19:57.333 --> 19:59.541
-Aren't we going swimming?

19:59.625 --> 20:02.208
Mom, what's wrong? What did she say?

20:03.666 --> 20:05.416
-You okay, Grandma?
-Mom, what is it?

20:05.500 --> 20:07.083
-Yes, I'm fine.
-Are you sure?

20:13.000 --> 20:15.250
-Grandma, can I go to the pool?

20:15.333 --> 20:16.333
Wait a second.

20:16.416 --> 20:18.416
-Nice to see you again.

20:20.291 --> 20:23.083
You guys, you go on down.
I'll meet you in the lobby.

20:28.250 --> 20:31.458
I just saw your email
with the paperwork attached.

20:32.083 --> 20:34.291
You have worked
with offshore entities before?

20:34.416 --> 20:35.541
Of course.

20:35.916 --> 20:39.250
Yeah, we did the same thing
in New York when we bought there.

20:39.333 --> 20:41.958
-Helps us with taxes and other things.
- Oooh!

20:42.375 --> 20:44.125
-Amazing!
- Now we're cooking.

20:44.208 --> 20:47.500
- That's great, Hannah. Incredible!
- I have all three on ho--

21:15.000 --> 21:18.875
So, how does it all work,
this world of offshore companies?

21:19.083 --> 21:21.000
And how do you know if it is for you?

21:21.333 --> 21:25.583
First of all, you must ask yourself,
are you wealthy?

21:26.166 --> 21:31.333
There are just over two thousand
billionaires on planet Earth.

21:31.875 --> 21:34.791
Maybe you are one of them,
or maybe you are just a millionaire.

21:34.875 --> 21:37.500
There are 15 million of them in the world.

21:38.458 --> 21:42.333
Perhaps you are older now
and it's time to contemplate your legacy.

21:42.541 --> 21:46.291
Or maybe you are younger and
building an empire like our friends here.

21:50.166 --> 21:53.416
<i>Your ambitions lead you to a place</i>
<i>that deals with money.</i>

21:53.750 --> 21:56.958
<i>For instance, a bank. A big bank.</i>

21:57.041 --> 21:58.541
<i>Probably in Europe.</i>

21:58.625 --> 22:03.000
<i>And you find yourself sitting</i>
<i>across a desk from a wealth manager,</i>

22:03.458 --> 22:06.208
<i>a financial advisor, a banker.</i>

22:06.291 --> 22:09.583
<i>You lay out your fears.</i>
<i>Income tax, state tax,</i>

22:09.666 --> 22:12.958
<i>inheritance tax, capital gains taxes.</i>

22:13.166 --> 22:15.500
Your advisor understands your concerns

22:15.583 --> 22:17.625
and suggests you set up
an offshore company,

22:17.708 --> 22:20.125
where your assets
will be safe from scrutiny.

22:20.208 --> 22:22.250
And that's where we come in.

22:23.375 --> 22:27.791
<i>Now, we supply you with a shell company,</i>
<i>which holds your assets.</i>

22:28.041 --> 22:31.000
<i>You are not the company,</i>
<i>even if the company is you.</i>

22:31.208 --> 22:34.416
<i>Confused yet?</i>
<i>We give this entity a name.</i>

22:34.625 --> 22:35.458
<i>Uh...</i>

22:35.833 --> 22:38.250
<i>"New Century Enterprises," perhaps.</i>

22:38.750 --> 22:41.666
<i>You don't need office space.</i>
<i>You don't need employees.</i>

22:42.083 --> 22:43.625
<i>Exists on paper only.</i>

22:43.833 --> 22:47.375
<i>And what does this company make?</i>
<i>What goods or services does it supply?</i>

22:48.208 --> 22:49.250
<i>Privacy.</i>

22:49.500 --> 22:53.291
<i>It's nothing more than an email address</i>
<i>and a post-office box in a country</i>

22:53.375 --> 22:56.208
<i>where the laws are favorable</i>
<i>to your financial goals.</i>

22:56.500 --> 22:58.708
<i>And where can you find such a country?</i>

22:58.833 --> 23:01.041
<i>Usually in the middle of the ocean.</i>

23:01.541 --> 23:06.000
<i>Maybe the Seychelles</i>
<i>or Cyprus or Tortola or...</i>

23:15.791 --> 23:17.791
I know it's not what you were expecting.

23:19.125 --> 23:21.750
Well, none of this is expected.

23:22.125 --> 23:23.666
Take the money, El.

23:24.375 --> 23:25.625
Sign the release.

23:27.000 --> 23:31.000
Joe took really good care of you
with his life insurance.

23:31.500 --> 23:32.833
That and the settlement...

23:33.791 --> 23:35.125
Just take a trip.

23:35.208 --> 23:36.750
-Miss some winter.

23:36.833 --> 23:39.583
Go somewhere that you always wanted.

23:43.291 --> 23:47.458
I mean, the damn insurance company
is the problem here.

23:48.625 --> 23:50.291
You know, I just don't--
I don't understand

23:50.375 --> 23:53.375
how they can just walk away
from any of this.

23:53.458 --> 23:56.708
The United Reinsurance Group of Nevis.

23:57.416 --> 24:00.166
They're the ones gettin' away with murder.

24:01.250 --> 24:03.250
Where in the world is Nevis?

24:03.500 --> 24:05.458
I don't know. Does it matter?

25:33.791 --> 25:34.958
Where's Boncamper?

25:35.041 --> 25:37.875
-Miss, you can't-- Oh, my God!
-Where is he? I want him!

25:39.916 --> 25:41.375
Where's Boncamper?

25:43.333 --> 25:44.458
Where is he?

25:53.250 --> 25:55.750
<i>Ladies and gentlemen, welcome to Nevis.</i>

25:55.833 --> 25:58.541
<i>The local time is approximately 2:45 p.m.</i>

25:59.166 --> 26:02.250
<i>There is no</i>
<i>Global Property Owners Association,</i>

26:02.458 --> 26:03.916
<i>and there is no Monarch.</i>

26:04.708 --> 26:06.000
<i>Never really was.</i>

26:07.125 --> 26:08.916
How is any of this possible?

26:09.000 --> 26:13.208
Purser backdated the letter to make it
look like he sent it before the accident

26:13.291 --> 26:14.666
so he wouldn't have to pay.

26:15.208 --> 26:16.750
What about United? Um...

26:16.833 --> 26:19.583
-They said United reinsured Monarch.
-No United, either.

26:20.125 --> 26:24.583
It's just a scam that goes from Houston
to the West Indies to Panama

26:24.666 --> 26:26.375
to some bank, who knows where.

26:27.208 --> 26:31.291
Looks like an 18 US code 1343, or 49.

26:33.833 --> 26:35.833
I'm sorry, 1340-what?

26:37.125 --> 26:38.125
Fraud.

26:41.208 --> 26:43.166
All I did wrong was try and save money.

26:46.041 --> 26:48.500
I tried to buy what I needed for less.

26:48.583 --> 26:49.583
That, and I...

26:51.041 --> 26:52.541
I trusted someone in...

26:54.916 --> 26:55.833
Houston.

26:57.208 --> 26:58.708
Is there even a Boncamper?

27:01.708 --> 27:02.708
Oh, yeah.

27:03.750 --> 27:05.083
There's a Boncamper.

27:06.416 --> 27:07.791
How long this time?

27:08.458 --> 27:09.583
Not sure.

27:10.958 --> 27:13.625
Three days. Maybe five.

27:14.458 --> 27:16.083
Clients coming in from Europe.

27:16.458 --> 27:17.416
Oh.

27:17.958 --> 27:19.041
Can I go?

27:19.875 --> 27:21.708
It's not vacation, Rich.

27:23.000 --> 27:27.750
If I bring you, I end up spending all
the money I make on the damn plane ticket.

27:27.833 --> 27:30.083
Come on, Dad, we can go to the uni.

27:31.708 --> 27:34.416
You-- You think I can afford
University Miami?

27:35.000 --> 27:36.750
You go there like every month, no?

27:37.000 --> 27:38.875
Why don't we get an apartment?

27:39.041 --> 27:40.958
In-state tuition is not that much.

27:41.041 --> 27:43.000
Oh, you know about the laws, do you?

27:43.625 --> 27:44.458
Mm?

27:46.625 --> 27:47.541
I do.

27:48.541 --> 27:52.750
I know all the residency laws.
That's what accountants know.

27:52.875 --> 27:55.041
Laws and taxes and banking.

27:55.708 --> 27:56.791
What do you know, eh?

27:57.583 --> 27:58.958
Basketball shoes?

28:01.666 --> 28:03.750
He want to see the world.

28:04.750 --> 28:06.416
Learn more about what you do.

28:07.416 --> 28:09.750
Maybe he can go into business
with you one day.

28:09.916 --> 28:12.291
Let him come along
and watch you at work, Irvin.

28:12.375 --> 28:13.625
Hmph.

28:41.875 --> 28:44.875
Excuse me, sir. Sir? Can you help me?

28:45.333 --> 28:48.958
I'm lookin' for 556 Main Street.

28:49.333 --> 28:51.291
Yeah? The post office, in here.

28:51.375 --> 28:54.833
No, I'm looking
for the United Reinsurance Group,

28:55.375 --> 28:57.625
which is 556 Main Street.

28:58.833 --> 29:00.625
-Un-- United, you say?
-Yeah.

29:00.833 --> 29:02.416
-Mm-hm.
-I-- I-- I-- I think...

29:02.500 --> 29:05.000
I-- I think you must have
written down the wrong address.

29:05.083 --> 29:07.833
No, no, I looked it up.
It's United Reinsurance.

29:07.916 --> 29:12.333
They reinsure, uh, pleasure cruises
and I'm sure other things, but...

29:12.541 --> 29:16.291
I'm actually looking for a man
called Bonca-- Boncamper.

29:19.458 --> 29:20.458
I don't know him.

29:36.333 --> 29:37.541
Daddy!

29:44.625 --> 29:45.708
Mr. Boncamper?

29:47.458 --> 29:48.458
Yes.

29:48.708 --> 29:51.833
Director of
the United Reinsurance Group of Nevis?

29:58.083 --> 30:01.166
Oh, my God, watch your sisters. Excuse me!

30:02.375 --> 30:03.625
Ma'am. Excuse me, ma'am.

30:03.708 --> 30:06.625
-Can you step away?
-I am his goddamn wife. Leave me alone.

30:07.208 --> 30:09.625
-Irvin.
-Vincelle Boncamper?

30:09.708 --> 30:10.666
Edith.

30:11.166 --> 30:14.333
Who the hell is Vincelle?
You people don't even know who he is.

30:14.791 --> 30:15.791
Irvin?

30:17.916 --> 30:19.333
Yeah. Edith?

30:21.666 --> 30:23.833
Can we speak privately for a moment?

30:35.666 --> 30:39.000
This woman, this is Vincelle Boncamper.

30:39.750 --> 30:41.916
-Your husband's other wife.
-What?

30:42.250 --> 30:45.333
Mr. Boncamper has another family.
They live in Nevis.

30:46.583 --> 30:47.958
You motherfucker!

30:48.208 --> 30:51.166
Get your hands off of me! You are dead!

30:51.583 --> 30:52.750
Gimme my kids.

30:54.250 --> 30:56.458
-Let's get him out of here. Let's go.
-Dear?

31:02.791 --> 31:05.833
<i>Final boarding call</i>
<i>for American flight 1307 to Lima,</i>

31:05.916 --> 31:07.833
<i>now departing at gate J-5.</i>

31:15.833 --> 31:17.500
<i>Excuse me. Mr. Mossack?</i>

31:18.083 --> 31:19.125
Yes?

31:19.208 --> 31:21.833
Do you know the name
Malchus Irvin Boncamper?

31:22.708 --> 31:24.125
I'm not sure.

31:24.208 --> 31:25.958
Is it a real name?

31:26.583 --> 31:29.458
Yes, sir. It's a very real name.

31:30.500 --> 31:31.958
How might I know it?

31:32.041 --> 31:33.333
He's from Nevis.

31:33.958 --> 31:35.708
It's a lovely island.

31:36.333 --> 31:38.666
He was arrested
at Miami International Airport.

31:40.541 --> 31:42.291
I think he's going to go to jail.

31:43.583 --> 31:44.625
I see.

31:46.041 --> 31:50.208
Well, maybe you'll tell me how well
do we know Mr. Boncamper?

31:50.291 --> 31:53.625
He's director of 46 different
Mossack Fonseca companies.

31:54.041 --> 31:57.416
The Prague offices use him quite a bit.

31:58.416 --> 32:00.708
Well, we will want to change that.

32:01.291 --> 32:02.875
Change that now?

32:03.791 --> 32:06.791
Can't really go back in time.
He's all over the books.

32:07.416 --> 32:11.666
Well, some people believe
that time is just an illusion.

32:12.458 --> 32:15.333
That all moments are the same moment.

32:16.500 --> 32:20.958
I think it might be bad for us
to do something like that.

32:22.916 --> 32:23.875
Bad?

32:25.625 --> 32:26.791
"Bad" is...

32:27.333 --> 32:29.375
It's such a big word

32:30.291 --> 32:32.375
for being such a small word.

32:33.291 --> 32:34.583
You did-- You did what?

32:34.666 --> 32:40.041
I went to the...  Clark County
Registrar to get the name of the buyer.

32:40.125 --> 32:41.916
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

32:42.000 --> 32:43.666
And I found out it's a company.

32:44.500 --> 32:47.083
New Century Enterprises of Panama.

32:47.166 --> 32:48.666
Wait, I thought you said it was Russia.

32:48.750 --> 32:50.750
-Russians with cash.
-No, that's what Hannah told me.

32:50.833 --> 32:53.208
-Hannah who?
-She's the realtor with the tight dresses.

32:53.291 --> 32:57.041
Anyway, I looked up
New Century Enterprises,

32:57.125 --> 33:00.291
and turns out it's controlled by a trust,
something called a trust.

33:00.375 --> 33:02.875
-A trust is like a fiduciary agreement--
-I know what a trust is.

33:02.958 --> 33:05.291
-A third party can-- Okay.
-I know what a trust is, I know--

33:05.375 --> 33:08.750
So the director of both New Century
and the trust...

33:08.833 --> 33:10.125
-...is a woman.

33:10.208 --> 33:12.458
A woman named Mia Beltran.

33:12.541 --> 33:15.583
Mia Bel-- Okay, is that
a name that I should know?

33:15.666 --> 33:19.208
Well, she is obviously very powerful.

33:19.291 --> 33:21.791
She is the director of numerous companies.

33:21.875 --> 33:23.375
-All her companies...

33:23.458 --> 33:26.125
...are registered
to the same law firm,

33:26.208 --> 33:27.208
in Panama.

33:27.291 --> 33:28.833
Mossack and Fonseca.

33:41.541 --> 33:43.375
Our database shows that you are

33:43.458 --> 33:46.333
the director of New Century Enterprises?

33:47.041 --> 33:48.541
I am, sir, yes.

33:48.625 --> 33:51.625
They have purchased multiple properties
in Las Vegas.

33:51.708 --> 33:54.041
I need these signed, immediately.

33:54.916 --> 33:56.666
<i> Moussaka Fusaka?</i>

33:57.375 --> 33:58.375
Oh, wait.

33:58.458 --> 34:01.375
Is that the new goalie for the Red Wings?
Canadian kid?

34:01.458 --> 34:05.875
No, no, no. No. No.
It's not a who. It's a law firm.

34:06.833 --> 34:08.791
In Panama. Okay?

34:08.875 --> 34:12.791
They even have a motto:
"The wealth management you deserve."

34:14.083 --> 34:15.708
I read that. I-- I looked it up.

34:16.166 --> 34:18.500
And our readers need
to know about them why?

34:18.583 --> 34:21.958
As far as I can see,
what they do is they set up companies.

34:22.125 --> 34:25.666
Uh, not real companies
like a hotel or a... hardware store.

34:25.750 --> 34:29.583
They-- They set up, uh, what they call
a "shell", and they sell shells.

34:30.083 --> 34:31.625
Not actual shells.

34:31.708 --> 34:33.583
I'm-- I'm sorry, you lost me. I--

34:34.208 --> 34:38.708
When there's an accident,
like the one that took Joe and Barb,

34:39.541 --> 34:41.791
there's nobody
that we can hold accountable.

34:41.875 --> 34:43.916
There's nobody that we can, uh...

34:44.000 --> 34:47.458
ask questions, and... and...
and find out what happens next, you know?

34:48.000 --> 34:49.041
It's just, uh...

34:50.208 --> 34:51.333
just empty shells.

34:51.708 --> 34:55.125
You see? It's just empty.
It's just shells.

34:55.208 --> 34:57.208
That's the story? Empty shells?

34:57.291 --> 34:59.250
Oh, no, no, the story is somebody died!

34:59.333 --> 35:02.500
And somebody's making money from it,
maybe lots of people.

35:03.833 --> 35:04.875
Right?

35:05.833 --> 35:09.916
That's why we brought it to you.
Somebody has to sound the alarm.

35:10.625 --> 35:13.583
W-- We like to focus on stories
that are closer to home.

35:14.791 --> 35:17.166
Where did you say
this company is located again?

35:19.125 --> 35:20.208
Panama.

35:20.791 --> 35:21.958
Like the hat.

35:29.416 --> 35:31.833
Jesus Christ, fix the goddamn roads. Fuck.

35:31.916 --> 35:34.666
Is it the road or bus
that has to be fixed?

35:34.750 --> 35:35.791
Both.

35:48.250 --> 35:50.208
Seems like we're not going anywhere.

35:50.750 --> 35:51.708
You can get off.

35:53.541 --> 35:54.375
Let's go.

36:24.416 --> 36:27.458
She was the director of 25,000 companies.

36:27.958 --> 36:29.958
-Mia Beltran.
- <i>Scheiße.</i>

36:30.375 --> 36:35.625
Now we need 25,000 forms
changing the director of these companies.

36:36.041 --> 36:39.000
<i>Mossack Fonseca.</i>
<i>How may I direct your call, please?</i>

36:39.458 --> 36:40.625
Oh, hello.

36:40.708 --> 36:43.083
Yes, I would like
to speak with Mr. Mossack, please.

36:43.166 --> 36:44.916
-Spanish.
<i>-Por favor.</i>

36:45.958 --> 36:49.041
No, he is in a meeting now.
Not taking calls.

36:49.416 --> 36:51.375
-He's meeting.
-Ask for the other one.

36:51.458 --> 36:54.750
Um... OK--
May I speak with Mr. Fonseca, please?

36:55.458 --> 36:59.916
He is in a meeting now too. Same meeting.
Maybe if I take a message...

37:00.625 --> 37:02.083
Uh, this is Ellen Martin.

